<TEXT>
the united states curtailed spy flights 
focused on colombian drug traffickers after allegations that a us 
aircraft nearly collided with two colombian planes a newspaper 
reported tuesday 
the defense department scaled back the program under pressure 
from the colombian government which had approved the missions on 
condition they be kept secret the los angeles times reported 
citing unidentified sources 
information from the spy flights has been used in a colombian 
manhunt for pablo escobar the reputed head of the medellin cocaine 
cartel the times said 
the alleged nearcollisions became public in colombia on march 
29 when the pilot of an sam airliner was quoted by newspapers as 
saying the military aircraft had passed within several hundred feet 
of his plane over southern colombia sociedad aerea medellinense a 
subsidiary of avianca normally flies domestic routes and to 
central america 
the pentagon has said that a panamabased air force ec130 
flying at 18500 feet had been in the area on march 28 but denied 
that a nearcollision had occurred 
a spokeswoman for the us embassy in bogota lauren hale on 
tuesday told the associated press that the only us government 
flights in colombia had been to practice search and rescue missions 
with the approval of the colombian government 
she said the united states decided to suspend the flights to 
prevent any further misinformation 
unidentified sources told the times that the ec130 a variation 
of the c130 cargo plane that carries electronic surveillance 
equipment is based at howard air base outside panama city 
bush administration officials said they believe the us pilot 
erred by allowing his plane to be spotted but they said the 
alleged nearcollision may have been conceived by colombians 
sympathetic to the drug traffickers according to the newspaper 
the pentagon has since ordered its spy plane pilots to avoid 
detection over colombia one official said it was possible the 
pilots may have to stay out of colombian airspace altogether 
the orders are believed to affect the operations of 
oklahomabased air force awacs radar planes that monitor air 
traffic over colombia and attempts by the panamabased ec130s to 
pick up communications among drug traffickers 
administration officials said the cutback could hurt 
intelligence gathering but that they were determined to maintain 
cooperation with colombian authorities in the drug war 
there will be a limit on what we can do but the bottom line 
in the long run is that we have to work with the colombians one 
source told the newspaper 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

