<DOCNO> AP900424-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two thieves shot yeh yungchuan to death 
in front of other investors as he left the trading floor of a 
brokerage house with nearly 100000 crime has come to taiwan on 
the heels of affluence 
yeh a 32yearold accountant turned to run when the men 
stopped him they shot him once in the back and once in the head 
took his 25 million taiwan dollars and fled on a motorcycle parked 
outside 
such brutal crimes are becoming common wealthy businessmen hire 
guards and use bulletproof cars 
taiwan is not safe anymore said rebecca yen a 28yearold 
employee of a trading company most of my friends plan to 
emigrate 
increased violence stems from a getrichquick mentality on this 
island of 20 million people abetted by guns smuggled from mainland 
china officials say 
police said a record 5839 cases of violent crime were reported 
last year and they confiscated 9770 firearms more than the total 
of the previous five years robberies increased 39 percent and 
kidnappings 53 percent from 1988 they said 
violent crime has jeopardized our social stability said jaw 
shaukong a popular legislator who wore a bulletproof vest in his 
december election campaign we dont feel as secure as before 
president lee tenghui acknowledged increasing crime has had a 
grave impact on social stability and the peoples confidence in the 
nation 
onethird of entrepreneurs responding to an economics ministry 
survey said they had been targets of harassment or extortion by 
gangsters 
last year taiwans richest shipping company executive paid 
nearly 2 million ransom for his kidnapped 32yearold son who was 
released unharmed police later arrested three suspects and 
retrieved the money 
many of the 145 kidnappings reported last year ended tragically 
captors killed several victims after ransom was paid 
four masked men armed with israelimade uzi machine guns shot up 
ho cheng securities in changhwa central taiwan in march 
apparently because the company did not pay 12 million in 
extortion money 
i dont think we can do any business when our lives and 
property are unprotected said kao chingyuan a taiwan business 
leader it may be safer to move our business abroad 
emigration appears to be growing along with the crime statistics 
thanks to soaring crime our business doubled last year 
said cc tai of domini international consulting corp which helps 
people emigrate to australia new zealand and canada 
tai estimated that about 40000 taiwanese left in 1989 up from 
30000 in 1988 
luxury cars seen as invitations to kidnapping and robbery no 
longer are in demand 
eric fang assistant sales manager of the largest mercedesbenz 
agency said his company sold only 290 cars in december down from 
the 1988 monthly average of 650 and predicted a drop in sales of 
15 percent for 1990 
many businessmen have postponed purchases because they do not 
want to drive the dangerous cars he said 
authorities report a dramatic increase in smuggled guns from 
china police said they seized 687 chinesemade shotguns last year 
up from 57 in 1988 
official statistics say smuggled chinese guns were used in 91 
killings in 1987 including those of four policemen 
premier lee huan has proclaimed 1990 anticrime year and 
proposed that gun possession now punishable by 10 years in prison 
be made a capital crime 
thousands of inexpensive guns are believed to be in the hands of 
gangsters some legislators say the only way to stop the influx 
from the mainland is for the government to hold direct talks with 
beijing 
the ruling nationalists fled to taiwan in 1949 after losing a 
civil war to the communists and still refuse to negotiate directly 
with the beijing government 
lin chiacheng a sociology professor at soochow university 
believes one reason for the crime wave is the widened gap between 
the rich and the poor 
taiwans exportled economic boom has made its per capita gross 
national product the fourth highest in asia but good fortune has 
not been shared equally the income of the top 20 percent is nearly 
five times that of the bottom 20 percent 
people also seem more inclined to seek quick riches than to work 
for a better life stock speculation has been the favored tactic 
but many have turned to crime 
traditional values have faded lin said fewer people 
believe in hard work and saving most envy those who have gotten 
wealthy fast from speculating and some think it is all right to 
get money from those rich people 
</TEXT>
