<TEXT>
soviet economists participating in a unique 
conference with their us counterparts took an even gloomier view 
of their countrys economy than western experts according to the 
events chairman 
the range of opinion for the soviet group was somewhere 
between pessimism and depression as far as the prospects for 
turnaround for the soviet economy said nicholas eberstadt an 
american enterprise institute scholar who was conference chairman 
the soviet analysts offered grim pictures of their countrys 
standard of living the size of its economy relative to other world 
powers and the burden its military places on the overall economy 
eberstadt said 
and he said at least one irony emerged from the fourday 
meeting soviet officials chiding the central intelligence agency 
for being taken in by soviet propaganda that overstated the 
countrys economic performance 
it was the sense of the group that the old official soviet 
estimates are not plausible he said 
the meeting was the first at which highlevel soviet economists 
have held frank exchanges with their us counterparts 
the conference report reinforced a downbeat view of the soviet 
economy released last week by the cia in congressional testimony 
agency deputy director for intelligence john helgerson called the 
economys 1989 performance abysmal and cited price increases 
and shortages of consumer goods 
although comparisons between market and nonmarket economies are 
difficult at best soviet economist victor belkin estimated his 
countrys gross national product is only 14 to 28 percent that of 
the united states that would rank it as low as eighth in the 
world behind the united states japan west germany france great 
britain italy and perhaps even india 
official estimates by the cia have ranked the soviet economy 
second after the united states putting it at about half the us 
gross national product of 53 trillion 
another soviet analyst vladimir tikhonov said his countrys 
agricultural statistics substantially overstate soviet food output 
meat production is barely half the officially reported figure he 
said grain output in 1988 was less than 140 million tons rather 
than the 195 million officially reported 
oleg bogomolov another conference participant put soviet 
military spending at 20 to 25 percent of gnp roughly 200 billion 
rubles a year that compares with the 77 billion rubles officially 
reported the cia estimate has been 15 percent 
the soviet level of military burden is more or less what north 
koreas is which means that it is a highly militarized society on 
a war footing eberstadt said 
another soviet researcher yuri dykhanov said the living 
standard of soviet citizens averages about 20 percent that of the 
united states the cia puts the figure at onethird the us level 
the idea that the soviet living standard might be as much as 
onethird that of the us standard struck the soviet group as 
utterly fanciful eberstadt said 
the soviet union is beginning new research in cooperation with 
austria and west germany aimed at finding better more accurate 
measures for its economy he said 
