<TEXT>
the government and home builders and groups of 
the handicapped are split over whether proposed guidelines 
guaranteeing disabled people access to new apartments would price 
many of them out of housing 
a task force formed by the national coordinating council on 
spinal cord injury and the national association of home builders 
said monday that the guidelines would put new apartment rents out 
of reach of many low and mediumincome people including the 
handicapped 
if design guidelines result in significant increases in the 
cost of housing then we have defeated the purpose of the fair 
housing amendments act of 1988 and created another barrier to 
accessibility said r jack powell president of the spinal 
injury group and executive director of the paralyzed veterans of 
america 
but gordon mansfield assistant hud secretary for fair housing 
and a former paralyzed veterans official contended in an interview 
that the guidelines are within congress intent and would add only 
1 percent to apartment rents 
housing and urban development secretary jack kemp has 
instructed us to pay attention to affordability and probably 
what we are proposing is less than the home builders said 
mansfield a paraplegic from a spinal cord injury suffered in the 
vietnam war 
bonnie milstein cochairman of the housing task force of the 
consortium for citizens with disabilities agreed she said the 
task force on handicap accessibility set up by the home builders 
and spinal injury group is basing its estimates on expenditures not 
required by the fair housing amendments 
congressional amendments to the fair housing act require hud to 
insure that disabled people have easy access to new multifamily 
apartments first occupied after next march 13 
the guidelines involve such things as the width of doors and 
halls the size of bathrooms and walkin pantries and the grading 
and ramping of steeply sloped sites 
the home builders and spinal cord council contended that the 
proposed guidelines will increase significantly the cost of 
apartment construction further slowing an already depressed 
multifamily industry and exacerbating the affordability crisis 
currently confronting millions of low and moderateincome 
households 
powell told a news conference at national association of home 
builders headquarters that the cost of meeting the proposed 
guidelines would range from 1300 to 3700 for walkup units and 
from 3200 to 4250 for mid to highrise apartments 
that cost he said will be passed on to consumers resulting in 
monthly rent increases of 13 to 37 for walkup units and of 32 
to 43 for mid or highrise units 
but mansfield said the hud guidelines would increase the cost of 
a 50000 apartment by just 1 percent or 500 which both hud and 
the handicap accessibility task force agree is within the cost that 
congress intended 
in addition to the disagreement over the effects of the new law 
the uncertainty over the guidelines has severely disrupted the 
multifamily construction industry said kent w colton executive 
vice president of the home builders 
he said the industry finished 1989 with only 373000 building 
starts down nearly 50 percent from 1985 and the lowest level since 
1975 
mansfield said the draft guidelines are being considered by the 
office of management and budget which much approve many government 
regulations before they take effect 
we would like to see the guidelines as soon as possible he 
said 
the home builders group is a federation of more than 800 
construction associations with more than 157000 members the 
coordinating council is composed of 17 organizations associated 
with spinal cord injuries of which the largest is the paralyzed 
veterans of america 
the consortium includes in its membership united cerebral palsy 
the american foundation for the blind and the easter seal society 
all three organizations supported the fair housing amendments 
