a federal judge in los angeles has demanded an explanation of 
how alvarez came to the united states if the doctor was kidnapped 
salinas said the incident could undermine the international 
drugfighting effort 
this runs the risk of creating illegal habits among those who 
have the obligation of defending the law and could create a problem 
much larger than the one we are trying to combat salinas said 
the mexican government has complained about the arrest of the 
gynecologist alleging the us drug enforcement administration 
offered money for the kidnapping and may have been in on the actual 
plot 
alvarez is alleged to have been present when camarena was 
tortured and murdered at a guadalajara house prosecutors allege 
that the doctor gave camarena drugs to revive him for additional 
torturing before he was killed 
the battle against narcotics traffickers requires 
unprecedented international cooperation salinas said 
but that cooperation in order to be effective and real has 
to be accomplished with the strictest international respect and no 
unilateral action against the law and rights of other nations he 
said it is not with arbitrary acts by the pursuers that we are 
going to combat the illegality of the narcotics traffickers 
us attorney general dick thornburgh has called for an 
investigation into the doctors arrest 
dea officials have denied allegations by alvarez lawyer robert 
k steinberg of los angeles that his client was kidnapped by 
bounty hunters who were paid as much as 100000 
the ap annual meeting included a report to the membership by 
william j keating chairman of the aps board of directors and 
louis d boccardi president and general manager of the ap keating 
is chairman and publisher of the cincinnati enquirer 
boccardi said that ap technology is advancing to meet the needs 
of its growing membership now at a record level 
aps electronic darkroom which will replace the current photo 
reception system is on schedule and meeting preproduction testing 
goals boccardi said 
fullscale installation of the ap leaf darkroom is to begin in 
september after summer fieldtesting an installation schedule is 
to be announced in june he said 
boccardi compared the new technology for electronic handling of 
photos to the computer terminal revolution in handling words he 
said it will mark a major step forward for newspapers 
we will train your staff and aps service reliability will 
stand behind the ap leaf darkroom it is the right step at the 
right time boccardi said 
he noted that darkrooms from sources other than ap could be used 
with the ap leaf which will fully conform to anpa standards 
other technological advancements are imminent boccardi added 
by july 1 the ap expects to complete the conversion of its 
entire highspeed system to deliver ap and supplemental copy to 
members at 9000 words a minute boccardi said 
a customized stocks service that allows members to localize 
market table pages is in print in a dozen member newspapers and 
the installation schedule for selectstocks will be accelerated 
through the rest of the year he said 
boccardi touched on the plight of terry anderson aps chief 
middle east correspondent who was taken hostage in lebanon five 
years ago last month 
we continue to search for an end to his ordeal and pray that 
recent optimistic comments will lead to his release boccardi 
said 
also at the meeting on monday david j whichard ii of the 
greenville nc daily reflector was elected to the board of 
directors of the associated press and five incumbents were 
reelected 
they were james k batten chairman and chief executive officer 
