<TEXT>
west german chancellor helmut kohl and 
east german prime minister lothar de maiziere today set july 2 as 
the target date for the economic monetary and social union of 
their countries 
while early july has frequently been mentioned as a goal this 
was the first bilateral announcement of a specific date 
the announcement read by west german government spokesman 
dieter vogel came as de maiziere met with kohl in his first visit 
to bonn as east germanys prime minister 
delegations from east and west germany will meet in east berlin 
on wednesday to begin negotiations on monetary union the bonn 
government announced earlier monetary union is a major step toward 
uniting the two german states 
the talks will cover bonns proposal monday to allow a 11 
exchange rate on wages salaries and pensions 
the 11 rate also would apply to savings accounts of up to 4000 
marks or about 2300 said kohl spokesman dieter vogel savings 
over that amount would be traded at two east german marks for every 
west german mark there had been reports west germany was 
considering the poorer rate for most savings 
the east german government had demanded the 11 rate to protect 
workers from higher living costs in a unified germany and the loss 
of huge subsidies that existed in the former socialist system 
east german politicians applauded the wage concession but 
criticized the limit on savings accounts 
west german opposition parties said the plan would cost 
billions erode the west german mark and lead to inflation west 
german stocks plunged to their lowest level of the year after the 
announcement 
west german finance minister theo waigel said his country will 
spend 35 billion to 58 billion over the next two years on 
unification 
many west germans who vote in national elections on dec 2 are 
worried they will bear the brunt of absorbing the crumbling east 
german economy 
the west german proposal is an important contribution to 
ending the disagreements between the nations east german 
government spokesman mathias gehler said 
but wolfgang ullmann vice president of east germanys 
parliament said if this is the final decision there should be 
sharp protest because a large part of savings will not be 
considered here 
meanwhile in east berlin monday east germany sent tons of its 
own money to the trashburner to make room in its treasury for the 
crisp new west german currency it hopes will bring prosperity 
soldiers stuffed sacks filled with old outofcirculation east 
german currency taking up space in the main treasury in east berlin 
the marks were carted off to the incinerator on monday so the 
government will have room for the new currency expected to begin 
officially circulating in the country by july 2 
the east german mark will not be needed with the introduction 
of the monetary union said the east german treasurys chief 
cashier horst boettcher 
in another step toward a single germany government sources in 
bonn said monday the four world war ii allies the soviet union 
united states france and britain will meet with the two germanys 
for talks may 5 on international aspects of german unification 
