<TEXT>
the interior department is proposing a new 
offshore oil leasing strategy it hopes will overcome congressional 
opposition to oil development and open the way for more drilling 
department officials said today 
the proposal was expected soon to be presented to president bush 
as part of a new fiveyear offshore oil leasing plan beginning in 
1992 
the revised proposal is aimed at breaking the political deadlock 
over expanded offshore drilling since president reagan opened the 
entire 14 billionacre outer continental shelf for potential 
development prompting outcries from environmentalists and many 
congressmen 
the new approach will be a lot more restrictive and lease 
sales will go a lot slower than in the past said barry 
williamson director of the departments minerals management 
service it will be a 180 degree change of what weve seen 
were taking a paring knife and were going to narrow and hold 
the process of offering leases down well do away to a large 
degree with the large areawide leasing concept williamson said 
in an interview 
the policies of the 1980s as they relate to offshore leasing 
are not working into the 1990s said interior spokesman steve 
goldstein he called the new approach much more realistic and 
said interior secretary manuel lujan hopes it will open the way for 
more offshore oil development 
the policy change was first reported in todays edition of the 
new york times 
williamson said that instead of considering vast expanses of 
offshore areas for oil development the department would draw 
boxes around areas that would be offlimits because of 
environmental concerns it would also single out areas where 
development should be pushed because of indications the prospects 
of finding oil would be good 
because the new concept would be more restrictive it may ease 
congressional opposition to the overall leasing effort interior 
officials said they said the areas that would be considered prime 
for development have yet to be determined nor how many acres would 
be considered for drilling 
only a small portion of the countrys outer continental shelf is 
used for oil and gas exploration mostly in the gulf of mexico 
congressional action has blocked development in vast areas along 
the atlantic and pacific coasts and off alaska 
bush is expected soon to announce his decision on whether to 
proceed with oil leases in three of the most controversial areas 
off the western coast of southern florida and off the california 
coast environmentalists and local citizen groups have strongly 
opposed drilling in the three areas 
officials said the new fiveyear plan would not be considered by 
the president until after his decision on the california and 
florida leases 
under interiors new approach the initial step of any leasing 
process would be to determine whether oil drilling or ship traffic 
would harm marine life and those areas would be withdrawn from 
consideration 
only areas where there is strong geological evidence of a 
potential oil strike would be put up for leases the plan also 
would share revenues from the leasing with coastal communities near 
the drilling sites in hopes of easing local opposition officials 
said 
the outer continental shelf a submerged ridge of land begins 
three miles offshore the petroleum industry has for years pushed 
for offshore development but efforts repeatedly have been blocked 
in most areas except in the gulf coast because of local opposition 
and freezes on lease sales imposed by congress 
