<TEXT>
norman cousins who in 1957 founded the us 
national committee for a sane nuclear policy received the niwano 
peace prize from a buddhist group tuesday for his work on behalf of 
nuclear disarmament 
the niwano peace foundation awards the 126000 prize each year 
to an individual or group deemed to have made an outstanding 
contribution to world peace through interreligious cooperation 
cousins devoted himself to the nuclear disarmament movement 
almost since the inception of nuclear weapons campaigning 
tirelessly for the reduction of nuclear arsenals both in the united 
states and elsewhere the foundation said 
in 1949 cousins established a foster care program for 400 
children orphaned by the atomic bombing of hiroshima he also 
arranged for people badly burned in the bombing to receive medical 
treatment in the united states 
an estimated 140000 people were killed in the us atomic 
attack on the city in the closing days of world war ii 
his combination of theory and practice have won him worldwide 
respect as a humanist impelled by love and compassion for 
humanity the foundation said 
the foundation was established in 1978 by rissho koseikai a 
japanese lay buddhist organization 
cousins was editor of the us magazine saturday review for 35 
years until his retirement in 1977 since then he has taught at 
the university of california los angeles he is also president of 
the world federalists association of the united states 
it has not been easy i recognize for japan to resist both 
national and external pressures to join the arms race of the 
superpowers cousins said in an acceptance speech 
cousins was selected from among 728 nominees from 121 nations 
