million of 1989 costs but so far exxon has declined to respond 
to that request alan raul told the house subcommittee on water 
power and offshore energy resources 
raul general counsel of the agriculture department is a member 
of the interagency trustee council trying to determine the 
environmental damages caused by the massive spill trustees said 
the first year of studies has cost 354 million more than twice 
the amount provided by exxon 
additional damage assessment studies this year could cost 30 
million according to an internal trustee council document made 
public by the house interior and insular affairs subcommittee 
cm harrison executive vice president of exxon co usa told 
the subcommittee that exxon doesnt plan to make further payments 
for damage assessments 
the process has not worked as exxon anticipated harrison 
said in prepared remarks adding that exxon has not had access to 
data collected as part of the assessment process 
exxon agreed shortly after the march 24 1989 spill in alaskas 
prince william sound to provide 15 million for longterm damage 
assessments interior secretary manuel lujan at the time 
characterized the payment as a first step with additional money to 
be sought from the oil company if needed 
the minutes of a march meeting of the trustee council quoted 
justice department officals as advising the council it should not 
expect further money from exxon according to a transcript 
released by the subcommittee 
the costs of damage assessment will be borne by the federal 
government although some of the money likely will be recovered as 
part of the damages sought in a civil suit expected to be filed 
against exxon 
the oil company has spent more than 1 billion to clean up the 
spill which contaminated miles of alaska coastline the justice 
department is pursuing criminal charges against exxon that could 
lead to fines and penalties of more than 600 million 
meanwhile several environmental groups called the federal 
damage assessement process inadequate and said that money shortages 
are causing the trustees to curtail some studies essential to 
determining overall damage to wildlife and natural resources 
the trustees decided at their march meeting not to proceed with 
24 of the 63 damage assessment studies 
the lawyers and not the scientists have driven the assessment 
process said erik olson of the national wildlife federation 
he contended that some of the studies were halted because they 
were too expensive and likely would not produce large payoffs in 
damage recovery as a result of the eventual civil suit against 
exxon 
apparently decisions on which studies to continue are based 
at least in part on financial considerations said robert adler 
a lawyer for the natural resources defense council 
members of the trustee council are officials of the agriculture 
and commerce departments and the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administration 
</TEXT>
