<TEXT>
solidarity cannot survive unless it makes 
a clean break with the government it created a prominent union 
activist warned tuesday as the labor federations congress neared 
its conclusion 
during the sixday congress delegates have sharply differed 
over what the unions role should be in a postcommunist poland 
whether it should remain actively involved in national politics or 
return to its trade union roots defending workers interests 
the union finds itself losing support among workers because of 
harsh austerity measures introduced by the solidarityled 
government under prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki a former union 
adviser 
the congress was scheduled to end tuesday but organizers said 
it might stretch into wednesday as debates continued on proposals 
for the unions draft constitution and program 
andrzej slowik a solidarity leader from the textile center of 
lodz said the labor movement must limit itself to purely union 
issues and cease trying to protect the government 
during the congress slowik has emerged as the chief rival to 
union leader lech walesa who has advocated a mixed role for the 
union combining politics with trade union issues 
his views appear to be gaining support among the 487 delegates 
even though he finished a distant second to walesa in saturdays 
election for the union chairmanship 
slowik has said it is clear that walesa intends to use the union 
chairmanship as a stepping stone to the presidency of poland 
the sooner walesa leaves us and goes to belvedere the 
presidential palace the bigger the chances to save solidarity 
slowik told the associated press in an interview tuesday 
otherwise solidarity may end its existence at the moment of the 
fall of the mazowiecki government 
walesa has waffled on whether he intends to launch a bid for the 
presidency now held by former communist party leader wojciech 
jaruzelski 
slowik said the union risks losing support if it remains too 
closely linked to the mazowiecki governments economic shock 
therapy program the reforms are aimed at reviving polands 
crisisridden economy and introducing capitalism 
the government has reduced inflation but nearly 300000 people 
or 2 percent of the workforce have lost their jobs so far this 
year as unprofitable stateowned enterprises are forced to close 
during the six days of the congress several more hundred 
unemployed were added in lodz he said 
mazowieckis solidarityled coalition was installed as a result 
of a political compromise struck by walesa in august to give poland 
the east blocs first noncommunistled government 
but recent opinion polls have shown that solidaritys popularity 
is falling as the union is being blamed for unpopular government 
economic measures which have hit hard at industrial workers the 
unions traditional base of support 
slowik said the union is suffering from sagging membership 
because of its leaderships decision to take care of the 
mazowiecki government instead of protecting the workers and its 
continued involvement in grand politics 
since regaining its legal status a year ago solidarity has 
recovered only 22 million of the 10 million members it claimed 
before the december 1981 martial law crackdown that forced the 
union underground for seven years 
slowik said he generally agrees with the governments reforms 
but wants solidarity to do more to protect workers from its 
effects including providing more job retraining programs and 
fighting for alternative factory costsaving steps to avert layoffs 
solidarity leaders close to walesa argue that the 10 million 
membership figure was exaggerated they attribute the membership 
decline to the emergence of many new political parties and 
associations during the past year 
on monday delegates to the congress endorsed a middle road 
passing up the opportunity to either remove the union totally from 
politics or immediately form a political party they approved a 
program plank that gives the union the option to eventually create 
its own political party and support candidates for parliament 
the union cannot leave politics totally but it should become 
more like a trade union especially in the present economic 
situation said delegate andrzej kunkiel from wroclawek in 
western poland 
solidarity which emerged as the east blocs first independent 
trade union during a 1980 strike wave held its only previous 
congress in the fall of 1981 just months before the military 
crackdown 
