<TEXT>
china agreed tuesday to provide credits to the 
soviet union to pay for the import of chinese consumer goods the 
official soviet news agency tass said 
the announcement came on the second day of premier li pengs 
visit here the first by a chinese head of government in 26 years 
the soviet union suffers from a chronic shortage of basic 
consumer goods ranging from toothpaste to matches and has 
increasingly turned to foreigners for help 
tass did not say what goods china would provide or give the 
monetary value of the deal 
for its part the soviet union will extend a credit to china for 
building a nuclear power station in china tass said the news 
agency also did not say how much that deal was worth or where the 
plant would be built 
the agreements on the credits were signed by soviet external 
economic relations minister konstantin katushev and chinese deputy 
foreign trade minister li lanqin tass said 
li met tuesday with soviet president mikhail s gorbachev who 
visited china last may 
lis fourday trip is intended to ease border tensions and 
improve relations between the longtime rivals for leadership of the 
communist world 
a good and interesting meeting thats how it was assessed by 
the participants soviet foreign ministry spokesman vadim 
perfiliev told a moscow briefing 
perfiliev said the leaders discussed further military cutbacks 
on the sovietchinese border and plans for strengthening economic 
ties 
tass said li and soviet premier nikolai ryzhkov signed an 
agreement on cooperation through the year 2000 that covers fuel 
and power metallurgy transport communications agriculture 
electronics forestry and environmental protection coooperation 
also is planned in health and space exploration 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze and his chinese 
counterpart qian qichen signed an agreement on mututal reduction 
of armed forces and military confidencebuilding measures along the 
two countries border the two countries have been negotiating the 
troop reductions for several years 
tuesdays agreement said soviet and chinese armed forces would 
be kept to a minimum corresponding to normal goodneighborly 
relations 
in their meeting gorbachev and li agreed that there is no 
single model for realizing socialist ideas each country has its 
own history own specifics own starting level of development and 
its impossible not to consider it tass said 
that theme was also evident monday when li made a speech 
emphasizing that his country and the soviet union have the right to 
tailor reforms to their own needs 
both are socialist countries and conduct reform and 
perestroika in accordance with the realities of their countries 
peng said in remarks reported by tass 
western diplomats in beijing said china has stressed it would 
never be a docile soviet ally as in the 1950s 
the ideological hardliners who now rule china reportedly blame 
gorbachev for the fall of communist parties in eastern europe and 
consider perestroika gorbachevs program of political and 
economic reform as a threat to socialism 
china and the soviet union split over ideological differences in 
1960 and fought a brief border war in 1969 in 1972 china restored 
relations with the united states in part because thenleader mao 
tsetung saw the soviet union as chinas most serious military 
threat 
