<TEXT>
for an hour tuesday the supreme court 
grappled with an important libel law issue contained in a former 
high school wrestling coachs 15yearold lawsuit against an ohio 
newspaper 
the court is being asked to decide whether the constitutions 
freespeech protections immunize all expressions of opinion as 
opposed to assertions of fact from libel lawsuits 
first however the justices may have to tell judges nationwide 
how to distinguish fact from opinion 
the factopinion distinction is important courts traditionally 
have barred libel suits over expressions of opinion even though the 
high court never has said explicitly that such protection is 
constitutionally required 
the justices spent much of tuesdays argument session trying to 
figure out whether to put a fact or opinion tag on a 1975 
sports column that accused michael milkovich of lying under oath 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices antonin scalia 
and anthony m kennedy asked the most questions all three seemed 
to consider the suedover statement an assertion of fact 
questions from justices john paul stevens sandra day oconnor 
and byron r white were more difficult to characterize justices 
william j brennan thurgood marshall and harry a blackmun asked 
no questions 
the suedover column was written by ted diadiun and appeared in 
the news herald of lake county published by the lorain journal co 
milkovich was coaching maple heights high schools wrestling 
team at a 1974 home meet against mentor high school when a melee 
involving both teams and spectators erupted several wrestlers were 
hospitalized 
diadiun who was at the meet wrote several articles criticizing 
milkovichs conduct 
in a jan 8 1975 column diadiun accused the coach and h don 
scott then superintendent of the maple heights public schools of 
lying to a judge who overturned disciplinary measures against the 
maple heights team 
during extensive litigation milkovich won two preliminary 
rounds before the ohio supreme court in a 1984 decision the state 
court ruled that diadiuns statements about milkovich were reported 
as fact not opinion 
but in ruling on scotts related libel suit two years later the 
ohio supreme court reversed its 1984 ruling and said diadiuns 
statements were expressions of his opinion 
in an unusual move the ohio court used its aug 6 1986 
decision in scotts case to doom as well milkovichs suit against 
the newspaper and diadiun 
holding up a 1975 headline that said milkovich beat the law 
with the big lie milkovich attorney brent english of cleveland 
told the justices this is quintessentially an assertion of 
fact 
but richard panza of lorain ohio argued for the newspaper and 
diadiun that when people read sports columns they expect to read 
opinion 
gusts of laughter filled the courtroom after justice kennedy 
responded i gave up reading sports columns because theres 
nothing but legal news in them 
panzas most persistent interrogator was justice scalia who at 
one point asked him doesnt it trouble you that peoples 
reputations can be destroyed this way 
