the senate agriculture committee voted tuesday 
to extend government programs for wool mohair and honey for five 
years with virtually no changes 
the wool and mohair title of the 1990 farm bill is 
essentially a fiveyear extension of the program for wool in the 
1985 farm bill said sen patrick leahy dvt 
the measure 
authorizes loans purchases and payments by the agriculture 
department to help the wool and mohair industry 
sets a payment rate that would be the difference between the 
national average of all domestic wool receipts and the price the 
government predetermined that producers should get each producers 
payment from the government would be calculated by applying this 
rate to net proceeds for wool sold the preceding year 
the honey section of the farm bill also would be little changed 
from current policies 
the price support for honey has dropped an average 5 percent 
each year for five years under the new legislation support prices 
would be frozen at 5686 cents a pound through 1995 
loan repayment rates would be unchanged 
