<TEXT>
the watchdogs charged with policing federal 
programs for fraud and abuse often farm out work to private shops 
leaving government oversight of a wide array of contractors in the 
hands of fellow contractors 
the governments inspectors general in reports to congress and 
in public statements attribute the hiring of private auditors and 
other contractors to severe staff shortages and they say most of 
the outside work is satisfactory 
but critics inside and outside the government say having private 
firms monitor private firms creates a weak link in government 
oversight of millions if not billions of dollars in contracts 
for programs ranging from running nuclear plants to job training to 
medicare 
documents obtained under the freedom of information act and from 
congressional investigators and other sources and information from 
recent interviews show that a handful of accounting firms led or 
heavily staffed by former government auditors get the bulk of the 
bigmoney contracts from the inspectors general 
a review by the labor departments inspector general said that 
in most cases it would be cheaper to hire a government worker 
most of the governments inspectors general use private firms 
working under contract to some degree and a handful have even used 
them to target other contractors for audits or possible prosecution 
in at least two cases both at the department of energy a 
private firm has been asked to review procurement to determine 
whether contracts the department awarded were wasteful or paid 
contractors too much 
for the most part the work is good but the standards are not 
always being met said a top aide to one inspector general 
its clear that having some of these audits was worse than having 
no audit at all it creates an impression of integrity that may not 
be there said the aide who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
inspectors general were added governmentwide in the 1980s in 
part because of congressional efforts to improve oversight as the 
reagan administration pushed to cut government payrolls and have 
more work performed by private contractors 
however inspectors general also faced staffing limitations 
leading them to turn to private firms to help police the growing 
number of private firms involved in government work 
one firm that does audits for several inspectors general also 
has provided three of five lecturers for a course in which 
contractors are taught to rebut government audits the firm 
leonard g birnbaum amp co recently ended its relationship with the 
seminar after congressional investigators brought it to the 
attention of the energy department 
several companies that receive energy department funding have 
sent employees to past seminars but a department official said he 
