<TEXT>
scientists have developed a more efficient way 
of breaking down a sugar in milk that cant be digested by many 
adult americans the agriculture department said tuesday 
an enzyme in the human body normally breaks down milk sugar 
lactose in dairy products but blacks asians and american 
indians tend to have a low level of this enzyme said george 
somkuti of the departments agricultural research service 
one solution is to add something to dairy products that does the 
work of the human bodys natural enzyme 
somkuti said researchers have developed a new source of the 
enzyme that is better than those now being used as additives 
because of its foodgrade nature 
the new source is an altered form of an organism streptococcus 
thermophilus which produces an enzyme that breaks down lactose in 
dairy products he said the food and drug administration has 
approved s thermophilus as a natural agent for making products 
such as cheese and yogurt 
somkuti said the altered bacteriums benefit is that it wont 
grow when added to milk however it splits lactose into two simple 
sugars glucose and galactose he said 
the new technique which is being patented by the usda agency 
could help people with lactose intolerance enjoy dairy products and 
thereby boost sales by milk producers officials said 
somkuti works at the usda agencys eastern regional research 
center in philadelphia pa the announcement was issued in 
washington by the agency 
