<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency is 
considering whether to impose a mandatory recycling requirement for 
major users of chloroflourocarbons or cfcs the agency said 
tuesday 
the chemical which is widely used as a refrigerant and as an 
industrial solvent is a principal cause of stratospheric ozone 
depletion and will be phased out over the coming decade in many 
countries including the united states 
but the epa said it was considering regulatory action aimed at 
getting users to recycle the chemical instead of letting it 
routinely into the air during maintenance and installation 
such releases have been common when mechanics work on automobile 
air conditioners or during repairs or installation of commercial or 
home air conditioners 
the epa said among the proposals that it was considering for 
possible rulemaking is a mandatory cfc recycling program that would 
be imposed on major users of the chemical nationwide another 
option would be a depositrefund system where users of cfcs would 
return cannisters of the chemical for a refund instead of venting 
the chemical the agency said 
many cfc users already have announced plans to shift to cfc 
recycling programs several of the major automakers for example 
have said within the next year they plan to provide dealers with 
equipment that would recycle cfcs used in automobile air 
conditioners 
the commercial air conditioning industry also has said it is 
developing recycling programs for the chemical 
