<TEXT>
the coming of high definition television wont 
reduce demand for american movies and television programs overseas 
a report to congress said tuesday 
the general accounting office said however that a single 
standard for overtheair transmission was necesssary to make us 
broadcasters and television manufacturers competitive with japanese 
and european satellite transmission of the new technology 
high definition television or hdtv offers a wider and sharper 
television picture than traditional television by increasing the 
number of horizontal lines that make up the picture 
television systems worldwide use different production formats 
and transmission standards because efforts to agree on a standard 
have been unsuccessful similarly there has been no agreement on 
standards for high definition television 
international broadcasters met last year but declined to adopt 
the standard developed by the japanese the socalled 112560 
standard 1125 lines per picture renewed 60 times per second 
current us television pictures use 525 lines per picture renewed 
30 times per second 
the absence of such a standard will not negatively affect the 
us entertainment industrys ability to successfully market its 
movies and television programs said the gao the congressional 
investigative arm 
the gao said representatives of the us entertainment industry 
were confident there would be no impact on international marketing 
because they sell their programs primarily on content rather than 
picture quality 
the us industry the largest producer worldwide of theater and 
television programs is likely to continue to produce movies and 
television programs using 35mm film the report said 
according to motion picture and television industry officials 
film is the highest quality production format currently available 
with about 2000 lines of resolution as a result it converts well 
to all current television standards and according to motion 
picture industry officials will also convert well to hdtv 
standards the report said 
however an overtheair transmission standard is needed to 
allow us broadcasters and television manunfacturers the 
opportunity to participate in hdtv gao found 
the lack of a transmission standard could be a competitive 
disadvantage with cable and satellite companies for american 
broadcasters who are constrained by regulatory and technical 
limitations of overtheair transmission the report said 
us exports of movie and television programs now contribute 
about 1 billion a year to the nations balance of payments 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

