commandos of the french secret service twice broke 
into nuclear power plants in 1987 in one case leaving behind two 
fake bombs as proof of lax security a newspaper reported tuesday 
le canard enchaine a satirical weekly known for its 
investigative reporting ran a photocopy of a letter apparently 
written by the state power companys security chief reporting to 
his superior about the second raid 
according to the letter two secret service agents carried out 
an undetected mock sabotage raid in october 1987 on the nuclear 
plant at bugey near lyon they climbed over an electrified fence 
placed two dummy bombs inside a cooling tower then set up a rocket 
launcher outside the letter said 
the other raid was conducted in march 1987 on the nuclear plant 
at nogentsurseine near paris with agents gaining access to the 
control room the newspaper said 
the paper also published a photocopy of a letter apparently 
from an interior ministry official informing officials in charge 
of the nuclear industry that a former member of the red brigades 
the italian terrorist group had been employed as a cleaner at a 
french nuclear plant 
there was no immediate official response to the weeklys report 
last week after le canard enchaine published a less detailed 
article on the same subject electric company official lucien 
bertron said a test raid was conducted at bugey in 198586 and 
described other parts of the report as pure fantasy 
