<TEXT>
newspaper publishers must move rapidly to 
recycle newsprint to prevent the government from moving in and 
imposing regulations the chairman of a publishers task force said 
tuesday 
frank a bennack jr president and chief executive officer of 
the hearst corp new york offered a report on recycling in his 
role as chairman of the american newspaper publishers association 
newsprint resource task force 
in an address to the anpas 104th annual convention bennack 
painted a grim picture of vanishing landfills to absorb the 
nations increasing output of solid waste 
he said publishers have resolved to double the amount of 
recycled newsprint used in the coming year reaching a total of 46 
million tons 
aggressive movement on recycling will prevent government 
intervention he said 
we believe efforts to control newsprint can mean efforts to 
control the press he said the prospect of dealing with a 
regulated newsprint industry calls up an array of terrifying 
unknowns 
bennack said that at least two states have already mandated that 
newspapers use recycled newsprint but he insisted such official 
orders will be unnecessary if publishers act on the recycling issue 
voluntarily 
he said 35 percent of newspapers currently are recycled and 
publishers aim to bring that up to 50 percent 
our goal must be reached if newspapers are to deal with the 
irrevocable closing of landfills he said 
bennack said the nation had 18000 landfills available in 1979 
today only 6500 remain and that figure will diminish to 4200 by 
1995 he said 
in 15 to 20 years the last existing landfills will be 
closed he said but this society will be producing thousands 
of tons of solid waste 
bennack stressed that although newspapers are among the most 
visible recyclable items they make up only 8 percent of solid 
waste going into landfills he said newspapers already are the 
second largest recycled material in the country 
</TEXT>
