<TEXT>
clifton reginald wharton the first black 
american to reach the rank of career minister and ambassador in the 
us foreign service has died at the age of 90 
the cause of death was not released 
wharton who died monday rose through the ranks of the service 
in his 40year career and ultimately was appointed ambassador to 
norway under presidents eisenhower and kennedy 
he also was an alternative representative of the united states 
at the united nations in the early 1960s 
wharton was the first black to be assigned as minister to a 
nonblack country the first to attain the rank of career minister 
and the first to become an ambassador through the career service 
born may 11 1899 in baltimore he earned several degrees from 
boston university and was the first black to pass the foreign 
service exam in 1925 
he soon was appointed vice consul and second secretary in 
liberia 
from 1930 to 1941 he served as consul in las palmas spain and 
from 1936 to 1942 held four temporary assigments to liberia as 
charge daffaires 
he went on to serve as a consul in tananarive madagascar a 
maritime consul in the azores portugal and consul general and 
first secretary in lisbon 
eisenhower named wharton envoy extraordinary and minister 
plenipotentiary to romania in 1958 kennedy named him ambassador to 
norway in 1961 and he retired in 1964 
he is survived by four children 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

