<TEXT>
communist symbols are vanishing from 
eastern europe but austria is keeping its hammer and sickle which 
had nothing to do with communism in the first place 
because neighboring nations in what used to be called the soviet 
bloc have been stripping wheat sheaves red stars and other 
communist symbols from their coats of arms the question also arose 
in austria 
in 1919 austrian legislators met in vienna to create a republic 
from the ruins of the austrohungarian empire they adopted a coat 
of arms in which the austrian eagle expressed commitment to the 
common man by holding a hammer for workers and a sickle for 
farmers in its claws 
in 1945 parliament voted to add broken shackles dangling from 
the eagles legs symbolize release from nazi domination 
the debate about what to do now has been spirited both in 
parliament and outside 
popular sentiment appears to be against removing the implements 
from the eagles claws of 24 letters from readers printed by the 
masscirculation tabloid kurier in march only five were in favor 
josef riegler one of the five said even during my first 
visits abroad after world war ii i was often asked whether the 
soviet occupiers had forced us to include the hammer and sickle in 
our state emblem i heard similar questions later from visitors to 
vienna 
some of those opposed to change expressed anger at what they 
considered an attempt by politicans to magnify a small issue 
others like brigitte michalko were defiant those who 
considered us communists up to now because of our coat of arms can 
continue to do so as far as i care she wrote 
the broken chains added in 1945 added to the existing confusion 
some saw them as an echo of the communist manifesto which exhorts 
the proletariat to rise because you have nothing to lose but your 
chains 
in february the rightleaning freedom party began efforts in 
parliament to discard at least the hammer and sickle 
they are symbols for contempt of humanity death camps and 
suppression the partys resolution declared if they remained on 
the national emblem it said austria would be the only 
noncommunist country in europe whose state symbol symbolizes 
communism 
although the measure received wide publicity it initially was 
considered more symbolic than serious the freedom party has only 
18 members in the 183seat chamber and few people thought the 
motion would receive the necessary twothirds vote 
the issue gained extra weight when a group of legislators from 
the austrian peoples party partner with the socialists in the 
governing coalition presented a similar motion 
sides were taken the peoples party split on the issue and the 
socialists opposed any change 
felix ermacora a sponsor of the peoples party motion said in 
an interview that changing the emblem could avoid 
misunderstandings abroad 
there is the occasional misconception when people look at our 
coat of arms on our passports for instance and see the hammer and 
sickle he said 
peoples party spokesman anton wressnig said the action by 
ermacoras group was independent changing the emblem is not an 
official concern of the party he said in a telephone interview 
and described the issue as relatively unimportant 
heinz fischer a senior socialist party official said if we 
didnt change it in 1956 and 1968 there is no no need to do it 
now 
soviet invasions crushed an antstalinist uprising in hungary in 
1956 and a reform movement in czechoslovakia in 1968 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

