<TEXT>
michael milkens plea bargain resolves his 
securities fraud charges but it remains unclear to what extent the 
junk bond pioneer will have to help federal investigators uncover 
other whitecollar crime 
milken heads to court today for a proceeding at which he is 
expected to plead guilty to six criminal counts and agree to pay 
600 million to settle the biggest financial fraud case ever 
brought against an individual 
the former drexel burnham lambert inc executive approved the 
plea deal friday after more than three years at the center of a 
highly publicized and contentious assault on wall street crime that 
began in 1986 
milken 43 had staunchly maintained his innocence but reversed 
course in the face of a threatened new government indictment 
replacing the 98 fraud and racketeering counts brought in march 
1989 sources have said the plea includes no insider trading or 
racketeering charges 
in an arrangement unusual for a major figure in the wall street 
fraud crackdown milken will not be required to provide 
investigators with information to build cases against other figures 
as part of the plea bargain sources said 
rather he will be questioned by federal officials after 
sentencing an individual familiar with the deal confirmed monday 
that arrangement would reduce the governments leverage by making 
it impossible for prosecutors to recommend a stiffer prison term if 
milken does not cooperate 
however the government still could control his prison 
conditions or parole date if investigators were unsatisifed with 
his help if he refused to testify under immunity before a grand 
jury milken could face contempt charges 
while the nature of milkens future cooperation remains unclear 
observers said the government was likely to seek details about 
extensive and possibly unlawful links with the nations savings and 
loans 
milken controlled a complex network of thrifts and corporate 
clients that bought and sold each others bonds financed deals and 
made investments together thrifts were among drexels largest junk 
bond customers 
the securities and exchange commission the house banking 
committee and the resolution trust corp which is charged with 
rescuing the nations thrifts are examining savings and loan 
failures expected to cost taxpayers hundreds of billions 
sec enforcement director william mclucas declined to comment on 
the reported milken settlement he did say the commission has 
formed a unit on thrift and banking that is examining compliance 
with securities laws 
asked what area milken is most likely to be questioned about 
john c coffee jr a securities law professor at columbia 
university said i think it would chiefly be the savings and 
loan people because the government would love to get the sampls 
the government isnt likely to get much useful information 
because of the terms of the deal coffee said 
he suggested the government may have agreed to the cosmetic 
cooperation in order to obtain the plea and save face following a 
series of light sentences in related wall street cases milken is 
expected to receive about five years in prison although he faces 
up to 28 years 
i think the government wants to offset these rather equivocal 
pyrrhic victories with a final round that shows this was a true 
crime coffee said 
he said the government may have been willing to trade away 
milkens assistance in nabbing other drexel and wall street figures 
in exchange for his guilty plea because theyre rosencrantz and 
guildenstern off in the wings and hes hamlet 
the plea deal leaves unresolved charges against former drexel 
trader bruce newberg who was named in the original 98count 
indictment and cases against individuals who were expected to be 
named in a new indictment 
