<TEXT>
junkbond pioneer michael milkens cathartic 
guilty plea to securities fraud today provoked reactions ranging 
from sympathy by defense lawyers to scornful snubs on wall street 
where many say his prolonged bout with the law helped taint the 
integrity of the financial markets 
the milken case was like a cleansing process that should 
restore investor confidence said john eric smith a floor 
official at the new york stock exchange when word broke of 
milkens tearful admission to six felony counts in a packed 
manhattan federal court 
the 43yearold former head bond trader for nowbankrupt drexel 
burnham lambert which revolutionized the securities industry with 
the use of highyield junk bonds that financed the takeover 
boom of the 1980s had insisted he was innocent for more than three 
years before changing his mind 
most of the counts to which he pleaded guilty were related to 
drexels relationship with speculator ivan boesky the convicted 
felon who provided much of the information for prosecutions of wall 
street corruption in recent years 
it was boeskys revelations about insider trading and other 
crimes that helped humble drexel and eventually drive it into 
bankruptcy court earlier this year putting 10000 people out of 
work 
milken faces a maximum 28 year prison term and must forfeit 600 
million in fines and restitution to defrauded investors but it 
will still leave him one of the nations wealthiest individuals 
i dont think well have to pass the hat for the guy you know 
what i mean said a middleaged nyse worker queried in lower 
manhattans financial district he declined to identify himself by 
name 
lawyers familiar with the milken case speculated the hardest 
thing for him to do was stand up in open court and admit he was a 
felon after insisting he was innocent for so long 
i think it was a fairly tragic and humbling proceeding for 
milken said theodore wells a lawyer who has represented other 
white collar defendants in fallout from the boeskydrexel scandal 
hopefully people will remember all of the good that he did for 
the financial markets and not focus exclusively on these apparent 
aberrations 
some said the charges in the plea agreement drastically fewer 
and less serious than the 98count racketeeringfraud indictment 
milken faced had he not pleaded guilty did not mean the government 
had let him off easily many believe milken will have to do some 
prison time 
whether its six counts or 26 counts it doesnt make a 
difference in the end and the message is the same said paul 
fischer a securities law attorney in washington and former 
securities and exchange lawyer who helped develop the investigation 
that eventually led to prosecutions of boesky drexel and milken 
six felony counts are six felony counts the exposure he has 
is still 28 years said ira l sorkin a former sec administrator 
in new york who now is in private practice 
its silly to play the game of who got the better deal 
sorkin said the fact of the matter is mr milken is a convicted 
felon federal prison minimum or maximum is not a very pleasant 
place 
</TEXT>
