<TEXT>
hitachi ltd is believed to be the first 
japanese company operating a research lab at an american university 
now that it has opened a biotechnology center at the university of 
california here 
hitachi officials said monday they hope the 165 million 
laboratory called plumwood house because of its plum color will 
allow the company to advance in areas like neuroscience and 
biochemistry where it has traditionally been weak 
hitachi has been devoting research in recent years to 
biotechnology but we are not advanced in this area said hiroshi 
sumiyama who heads the lab 
thats why the company decided to locate the facility in the 
united states which is more advanced in biotechnology research 
uci gave us the opportunity to do this he said 
uci leased 1 acres to hitachi for 40 years in return uci 
researchers can use 15000 of the 40000squarefoot building 
called plumwood house 
the university is getting great laboratory space at no expense 
to the taxpayers said john wasmuth one of three uci researchers 
assigned to the lab 
the lab will be used by 60 hitachi and uci researchers 
state officials noted the venture will benefit both the 
university and hitachi while any discoveries by lab researchers 
will go to uci 
its not going to succeed if the general public does not 
benefit before hitachi said allan melkesian director of the 
state office of foreign investment there is going to be a lot of 
scrutiny as there ought to be it is a sensitive area 
foreign investment on college campuses is not new a consortium 
of german companies built a computer science building at the 
university of california berkeley campus and a japanese 
pharmaceutical company is constructing a lab at the uc san diego 
campus 
four us corporations including texas instruments have 
established laboratories at japanese institutions 
another japanese electronics giant nec corp plans to open an 
artificial intelligence laboratory in princeton nj next month 
nec is spending 75 million for the project and company officials 
say they intend to recruit researchers from princeton university 
joint ventures between japanese companies and american 
universities are likely to grow according to richard king a los 
angelesbased international trade consultant 
i think we will find many more of these kinds of ventures 
where the japanese want to tie in with research and development and 
hightechnology endeavors and the universities welcome that 
because its a privatepublic sector relationship where benefits 
accrue to both sides king said 
