<TEXT>
four major corporations and a computer software 
company said tuesday they formed an alliance to develop software 
that will allow them to better manage corporate knowledge or 
the skills and knowhow of their employees 
the five companies digital equipment corp ford motor co 
texas instruments inc u s west inc and carnegie group inc a 
pittsburghbased software company said they contributed 10 
million to the initiative which they began in 1988 but did not 
announce at the time 
the alliance called the initiative for managing knowledge 
assets is aimed at developing a nextgeneration software that will 
capture the skills and knowledge of a companys employees and make 
it available to others through a computer system 
the ability to manage these assets just as companies manage 
their capital or financial assets is one of the most important 
ways in which companies can retain a competitive advantage in our 
increasingly competitive world said ted smith technical 
director of u s west advanced technologies inc a division of the 
coloradobased regional phone company 
among knowledge skills of employees are design experience 
engineering skills financial analysis marketplace knowledge and 
knowledge of a companys policies practices and goals the 
alliance said 
the group calls the computer technique it intends to develop 
knowledge processing 
the five companies said they will use the software they develop 
in their own operations and sell products based on it smith 
invited other companies to join the nonprofit group 
smith said the companies hope the software they develop will 
help them bring products to market faster and improve customer 
service the group already has spent a year in engineering 
development of the software it said 
the group said it will use concepts developed in artificial 
intelligence research such as expert systems programs but that 
the software will not be an artificial intelligence application per 
se 
artificial intelligence is a type of software than attempts to 
mimic the way humans think expert systems programs attempt to 
capture the knowledge of a human expert such as an engineer or 
doctor and make it available through a programming technique 
called inference in which conclusions are drawn about a problem or 
question through a series of logic questions such as ifthen 
clauses 
the companies said they decided to form the group after they 
found nothing on the market to provide the type of computer program 
they need 
the group said it plans to have its core technology available 
for testing by this fall 
michael l schneider a computer analyst at the research firm 
gartner group inc said the alliance represents the first time a 
group of endusers of computer services has decided to set the 
standards for a new computer technology at its infancy 
currently he said expertsystems programs are not 
standardized under the software the group intends to develop it 
means everybody will be speaking the same language which could 
speed the growth of such programs he said 
gibbs r moody a software analyst at the san francisco 
brokerage hambrecht amp quist said texas instruments digital u s 
west and carnegie group have been working on artificial 
intelligence systems on their own 
moody said the alliance sounds like a small significant step 
but nothing earthshattering 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

