<DOCNO> AP900424-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are the six federal securities and tax law 
violations outlined in financier michael milkens guilty plea in 
us district court on tuesday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
conspiracy 
the government said milken former stock speculator ivan f 
boesky drexel client david solomon of solomon asset management and 
others conspired to violated federal tax and securities laws 
the conspiracy involved transactions detailed in the five other 
counts including illegal stock trades hidden from federal 
regulators secret records kept separate from drexels official 
books tax evasion and federal securities rules violations 
the government said milken and the others profited from 
transactions while investors were cheated 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aiding and abetting the filing of false documents with the 
securities and exchange commission 
the government said the violation was designed to help boesky by 
concealing his stock holdings in fischbach corp a construction 
business that was the subject of a takeover attempt by pennsylvania 
engineering corp 
milken admitted that he failed to record a deal compensating 
boesky for trading losses in fischbach from april 1984 to february 
1985 boesky had acquired more than 10 percent of fischbach on 
milkens recommendation and milken promised to to cover any trading 
losses 
the government said boesky lost several million dollars buying 
fischbach stock which drexel more than made up for under the 
secret arrangement 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
securities fraud 
milken admitted to arranging a secret purchase by boesky of mca 
corp stock held by drexel client golden nugget inc from march to 
november 1984 
golden nugget a las vegasbased casino operator had purchased 
99 million in mca stock during a planned takeover of the 
entertainment giant the government said milken induced boesky to 
buy about 875000 shares of mca stock to try to hide from the 
market that golden nugget was dumping its position 
the move was designed to prop up the price of mca stock which 
would have fallen if word of the large sales by golden nugget 
became public boeskys illegal purchases created the false 
appearance of wide market demand 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aiding and abetting the violation of sec reporting requirements 
for brokerdealers 
the government said drexel in 1985 bought about 1 million shares 
of helmerich amp payne corp stock worth more than 20 million from 
boesky and agreed to hold the stock for boesky who in turn 
promised to to make up any losses suffered by drexel drexel later 
sold some of the stock back to boesky 
the deal allowed boesky to cheat on his taxes free up cash to 
buy more stock and overstate the amount of net capital in his 
seemala corp the government said by failing to report the stock 
sales milken helped boesky violate federal laws the government 
said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
mail fraud 
milken said he persuaded solomon to become a manager for 
finsbury group ltd a drexelorganized international investment 
fund 
drexels junk bond department in beverly hills calif paid 
fees to salesmen who marketed the finsbury shares and solomon then 
funneled money back to the junk bond department by setting up deals 
between drexel and solomons clients 
the government said milken adjusted transaction prices to 
provide cash that could go back to drexel but solomons clients 
were kept in the dark about the arrangement the arrangement 
involved transactions from 1984 to 1986 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aiding and abetting the filing of a false tax return 
milken admitted setting up prearranged trades that allowed 
solomon to claim shortterm capital losses and reduce his 1985 tax 
liability 
milken and solomon set up the deal with an understanding that 
milken would pay back solomon for his losses the following year 
milken in 1986 let solomon acquire a limited partnership interest 
that solomon sold for a profit that was higher than the earlier 
bogus losses the government said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
