<TEXT>
despite a lastminute attempt by 
opponents to buy more time the pennsylvania house on tuesday sent 
gov robert p casey a bill that would enact the nations toughest 
curbs against hostile takeovers 
after a brief debate the house approved the bill 18317 the 
senate gave its final backing to the measure monday 
casey has said he would sign the bill administration spokesman 
john taylor said the governor has 10 days to act on it 
supporters of the measure praised its protections for workers 
and said it would help business thrive in pennsylvania 
rep marvin e miller jr said the bill would serve as the 
fundamental basis for economic development for the future 
by passing this were sending a loud and clear message that 
people cant make simple quick chop shops out of our 
corporations he said 
the republican lawmaker represents the city of lancaster whose 
leading employer was the target of a takeover attempt that spawned 
the bill the belzberg family of canada last year tried to take 
over armstrong world industries inc a floor and tile manufacturer 
under the bill a raider who tried to sell shares within 18 
months of a takeover bid would be forced to give up shortterm 
profits the bill also would deny raiders voting rights until a 
majority of a corporations stockholders approved 
passage came easily despite gloomy warnings the bill would make 
pennsylvania less competitive with other states and would protect 
bad managers 
this is bad for labor in pennsylvania bad for pennsylvania 
business and bad for the state of pennsylvania said rep robert 
godshall this would strip any basic and fundamental rights of 
stockholders 
the bill also would allow management to weigh the interests of 
employees customers or the community rather than just 
shareholders when considering takeover bids 
if corporate ownership changes hands labor contracts would have 
to be honored and severance would be paid to laid off workers up 
to 90 days after the law takes effect corporations would be able 
to exempt themselves from the legislation 
members of the investment community including the chairman of 
the securities and exchange commission have criticized the bill 
saying it would entrench management and deny shareholders rights 
with the junk bond market in shambles and takeovers on the wane 
some critics have argued that the legislation is overkill 
but supporters including state business and labor interests 
argue it will protect jobs and communities while giving 
shareholders longterm stability 
william titelman lawyer for the belzberg family predicted the 
bill would scare investors from putting money into pennsylvania 
corporations 
i think its a very sad day a dangerous day because we are 
now confronted with a bill that has been properly perceived by 
investors across the country and even overseas as a piece of 
legislation which tells them that pennsylvania is not a good place 
to invest titelman said 
