investigation of him for alleged racketeering and other crimes 
but friends and beneficiaries of milkens largesse say his 
charity work began long before the probe and was performed with an 
intensity mirroring his deal making particularly when children 
were involved 
some people make snide remarks and say hes just trying to 
atone said melba f coleman the principal of 102nd street 
school in watts i say look at the record he didnt just start 
this when he was indicted 
milken taught math at the elementary school for a day recently 
bringing along pop star michael jackson as a treat for the children 
in the economically depressed area 
milken brought in fruit vegetables and calculators to 
illustrate his lessons and had to be dragged away from the students 
at the end of the day said mrs coleman he called back to 
volunteer again even before shed written him a thankyou note she 
added 
i tell the kids you need to dream big you need role 
models mrs coleman said im sure he made a difference for 
them 
jules lesner the director of the foundations of the milken 
families said their operations will be unaffected by milkens 
guilty plea tuesday to six felonies 
publicity about those pleas and the 600 million in fines and 
restitution milken agreed to pay will mean just an increase in 
the number of requests lesner said more people are aware 
were here and what we do 
milken and his brother lowell have established four foundations 
in all with endowments that now total nearly 400 million 
operating out of offices not far from milkens home in the san 
fernando valley they fund educational programs and awards to 
educators health care cancer and epilepsy research child care 
museums job retraining sports programs 
a jewish community center in the west san fernando valley was 
built with millions of dollars in foundation money children at the 
los angeles zoo can enter a cave to learn about pallid bats and 
ringtail cats and a desert area to study sidewinders and gila 
monsters thanks to a 1 million donation 
another 1 million went toward the museum of tolerance the 
jewish holocaust education facility under construction at the simon 
wiesenthal center in west los angeles 
his involvement with our charity goes back many years to at 
least 1983 said rabbi marvin hier of the wiesenthal center 
whenever we asked him to do something it was always a 
personal involvement never just sending a check 
when michael milken would speak to you about charitable 
projects he would make it sound as if you were the most important 
person in the world and you were the only person he was concerned 
with at that moment hier said 
even in charity milkens activities were questioned rep john 
d dingell dmich who heads the house subcommittee on oversight 
and investigations asked the california attorney generals office 
to determine if milken illegally benefited from the foundations 
trades or assets after a ninemonth probe investigators reported 
last august that he had not 
richard riordan a friend of milkens who is a lawyer and fellow 
philanthropist said milken genuinely loves dealing with children 
especially minority children 
his attitude is sort of an underdog its a bit of the jewish 
culture the underdog culture the ethic that they have to give to 
others but theres something very special about him anything he 
does hes handson riordan said 
riordan said he expects milken to continue his charitable work 
from behind bars if he goes to prison 
at the 102nd street school mrs coleman said some teachers had 
gone out of their way to make sure she heard their criticism of 
milken accusing him of selfpromotion for his visit 
the children felt differently she said 
today some of them seemed kind of sad she said they 
were saying will he come back will he have to go to jail 
